{
  "card_id": "lower_time_frame",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Lower Time Frame",
  "aliases": [
    "hourly time frame",
    "Hourly Time Frame",
    "ltf",
    "LTF"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A chart time frame below the bias or confirmation time frame, used to refine entries at higher time frame points of interest. It reveals internal price delivery and enables confirmation of displacement, change in state of delivery, SMT divergences, and PD arrays (order blocks, fair value gaps) for precise entries with tighter stops.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Establish bias and identify a point of interest (e.g., PD array, fair value gap, liquidity level, session high/low, range) on the higher time frame before moving to the lower time frame.",
    "Select a lower time frame based on a fractal pairing (daily→hourly, hourly→5-min, 15-min→1-min) or simply a frame smaller than the bias chart.",
    "Wait for price to reach into the higher time frame point of interest, then seek confirmation patterns on the lower time frame: displacement, change in state of delivery (close through opposing candle series), SMT divergences, or PD array entries (order blocks, fair value gaps, breakers) that align with the higher time frame bias.",
    "Validate lower time frame setups by requiring a change in state of delivery (closure through opposing candle series) at the higher time frame level, forming a protected swing, before entering.",
    "Use lower time frame tools such as the OTE (0.62–0.79 retracement) of a displacement leg, or the 0.5 level of a higher time frame wick, to refine entry within the higher time frame point of interest.",
    "Only consider lower time frame setups that occur within the higher time frame point of interest, range, or deviation zone; ignore patterns lacking higher time frame context.",
    "Observe the lower time frame's internal price delivery to anticipate the nature of a developing higher time frame candle (directional, reversal, or indecision) based on price sequence smoothness and wick structure.",
    "Confirm the lower time frame order block aligns with a key session time (e.g., 08:30 or 09:30 New York open) for additional confluence before framing an entry."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "The lower time frame allows execution of precise entries with tighter stops after a higher time frame point of interest is identified. Traders drop to the lower time frame to confirm displacement, change in state of delivery, or PD array alignments with the higher time frame bias, often using OTE retracements or wick respect. Entries target session liquidity or deviation projections for at least 2R. Without higher time frame context, lower time frame patterns are considered noise.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Attempting to use the lower time frame entry before the higher-time-frame key level (PD Array) has been reached, resulting in premature entries against the prevailing move.",
    "Relying solely on the working time frame (e.g., 15M) when price action is 'messy' and a clear series of same-direction candles cannot be identified, instead of dropping to the LTF for a cleaner read.",
    "Missing the lower time frame order block formation at 09:30 (New York opposing run) by not monitoring the LTF during key session times, thereby entering late or at a worse price.",
    "Taking an LTF entry without first establishing higher time frame bias and a point of interest, or misinterpreting LTF patterns as setups when no HTF level is present.",
    "Entering on LTF without confirming displacement, change in state of delivery, or valid HTF context (e.g., OTE, PD array alignment).",
    "Taking LTF setups that oppose the higher time frame bias.",
    "Using the lower time frame to form bias rather than for entry refinement.",
    "Looking for LTF setups on a time frame equal to or higher than the fractal pairing, or outside the HTF point of interest/range.",
    "Forcing a trade after price closes through the 0.5 wick level on the LTF, or expecting perfect respect every time.",
    "Interpreting early LTF price movement as the final candle direction before the HTF candle completes, leading to premature entries.",
    "Continuing to look for LTF continuation after the LTF point of interest has been invalidated by a close back over it."
  ],
